<div class="flex flex-col gap-5">
	<p>
		Kyle McDonald starts from a position of responsibility. Researchers and engineers push technology forward. Artists tear it apart. Misuse is the specific job artists are positioned to do. When a system fails, it shows you its assumptions. When you break something, you learn what it was actually built for.
	</p>
	<p>
		<em>Facework</em> makes this argument with full absurdity intact. It's a game set in a near-future gig economy where players have to pass as certain types of people to get hired for increasingly strange jobs. To prove you'd make a good patient for a trainee dentist, you have to hold your mouth wide open. To prove you'd make a cool babysitter, you have to show you're wearing sunglasses. The game runs on real face detection neural networks, the same feature extraction that corporations have researched for over a decade. Blonde hair, big nose, mustache, sunglasses. Players try to fool it in real time, usually by covering their face with their hands and watching the feedback until the system decides they're wearing sunglasses. In that moment, the glitch is exposed. The audience builds intuition for how the system really works, not through explanation but through direct contact with its failure.
	</p>
	<p>
		The deeper interest is in knowledge that AI presents as settled when it isn't. When McDonald asked an early ChatGPT about ancient Pacific seafaring traditions, it answered confidently and got everything wrong. The information he'd gathered from conversations with elders in Fiji, the Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea, stories never written down, never digitized, never entered into any training corpus, simply didn't exist in the model. That gap between the archive and the living knowledge held in relationships and in places is where he keeps returning. The humpback whale song project has to be trained from scratch because no existing AI can do it. Some knowledge has never been digitized. Some of it never will be.
	</p>
	<p>
		Creation begins where knowledge ends. McDonald agrees, though he'd put the emphasis on curiosity. Curiosity lives at the edges of what's settled. Artists have a responsibility to stay there. To unsettle the settled. To ask the questions that science will eventually answer, and to keep making trouble in the meantime.
	</p>
</div>
